                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Picture of the New Coates Hotel&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>BROADWAY.<lb/></p>
            <p>THE NEW COATES.<lb/>
                ABSOLUTELY FIRE PROOF<lb/>
                THE LARGEST AND FINEST HOTEL IN THE CITY.<lb/>
                COATES HOUSE MANAGEMENT CO.<lb/>
                PROPRIETORS.<lb/>
                J. L. COATES&#44; PRES&#39;T &#38; MANAGER.<lb/>
                A. C. COATES&#44; SEC&#39;Y &#38; TREAS<lb/>
                C. G. BAIRD&#44; ASS&#39;T MANAGER.<lb/>
                COATES<lb/> OPERA HOUSE<lb/> ON DIAGONAL<lb/> CORNER.<lb/> BEST<lb/> ATTRACTIONS<lb/> ONLY.<lb/>
                KANSAS CITY&#44; MO. Apr 23rd 1894<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Father<lb/></p>
            <p>Last night I sent a spec&#45;<lb/>ial delivery letter&#44; to Nina telling her<lb/> that I had accepted a promising<lb/> position in Cawker City Kansas&#44; I<lb/> wrote to her instead of you&#44; for I knew<lb/> how much you have on your mind<lb/> at present.<lb/></p>
            <p>To say that I sympathize<lb/> with you would not begin to express<lb/> how I feel for you and Rebecca and<lb/> all&#44; you said in your last letter<lb/> which informed of sweet little Garry&#39;s<lb/> death&#44; that you would be happy<lb/> if you could always hear that I am<lb/> on a good path&#44; every future act of<lb/> mine will prove to you that I<lb/> <hi rend="underline">will do right</hi> and in the future<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>you will hear nothing but good of<lb/> me&#44; and from me<lb/></p>
            <p>I accepted the<lb/> position in Kansas because the<lb/> business and weather continue dull<lb/> here&#44; and Mr. Weil will give me<lb/> a show later anyhow&#44; then this<lb/> man wants me badly and will<lb/> increase my salary according to<lb/> my ability and the state of trade&#44;<lb/> I leave behind me three staunch<lb/> friends&#44; Mr. Coy&#44; Mr. Simms&#44; and<lb/> Mr. Weil&#44; all advised me to accept<lb/> this place for the present anyhow&#44;<lb/> Cawker City is 250 miles from<lb/> here and has a population of 1600<lb/> as near as I can ascertain.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mr Coy arrived home last<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>evening&#44; and I have been with<lb/> him nearly all day&#44; I took lunch<lb/> with him&#44; he leaves to&#45;morrow<lb/> for the country&#44; he has implicit<lb/> confidence in  me and he and Mr.<lb/> Simms also promise me good places<lb/> when they have them.<lb/></p>
            <p>If you write by<lb/> Thursday or Saturday night address<lb/> to c&#47;o Jacob Rothschild<lb/> Cawker City<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Kansas</hi><lb/> With love and hoping<lb/> <hi rend="underline">all</hi> are <hi rend="underline">well</hi>.<lb/>  Good Bye.<lb/> Leon<lb/></p>
            </body>
